# Chart the JoelClaw Video Pipeline

## Finish line

A durable Mux/Inngest video publishing pipeline living in `joelhooks/joelclaw-video` and consumed by joelclaw's system-bus: any agent or CLI hands it a pointer to a video and gets back a shareable watch URL, with draft/published and public/unlisted/private states backed by local Convex. The long game is a personal Loom replacement that agents can publish through on Joel's behalf.

The first proof is phase 1: a filesystem path on flagg goes in, a Mux asset/playback id comes out. The map is done when phase 1 is live, the agent publish surface is decided, and the watch-page phase is fully specifiable.

## Notes

### Fixed direction (decided in the 2026-07-13 charting grill)

- **Deploy shape:** `joelclaw-video` is a standalone repo publishing a package; joelclaw's `packages/system-bus` imports it and registers its Inngest functions alongside the existing 110+. One Inngest app; the existing mux webhook provider (`packages/system-bus/src/webhooks/providers/mux.ts`, secret already leased in `serve.ts`) just works.
- **Ingest:** Mux direct upload — create an upload via the Mux API and PUT the bytes from flagg. No public exposure, no staging required for phase 1. Asset settings must include a progressive/downloadable rendition — mirror course-builder's `getMuxOptions` (`packages/core/src/lib/mux.ts`: `video_quality: plus`, `max_resolution_tier: 2160p`, `mp4_support: standard`, generated English subtitles) but verify against current Mux docs; `mp4_support` may have been superseded by `static_renditions`.
- **Metadata store:** local Convex mirrors course-builder's content-resource shape for video resources. States: draft/published crossed with public/unlisted/private.
- **Originals:** archived (NAS/Garage) alongside Mux, with easy TTL-based cleanup so the archive doesn't fill with shit. Mux is the delivery layer, not the only copy.
- **Watch page:** a real one is part of the destination — not just `player.mux.com` links.
- **Transcripts (added 2026-07-13):** super important, and via **Deepgram** the way course-builder does it — not Mux's auto-generated captions. Running course-builder locally is a legitimate aid for studying its flow. Existing prior art: joelclaw's mux webhook receiver on flagg is verified live (see Decisions so far), and `media-transcription-pipeline.ts` already speaks to transcription.
- **joelclaw-api (Joel, 2026-07-13, during the Convex-model grill):** pipeline mutations flow through a new generally-useful application layer, not direct Convex clients scattered in Inngest functions. Stack intent: Hono(?), pocock-quality TypeScript 7, effect-smol (Effect v4), XState v5, oxfmt/oxlint/ultracite; MCP and CLI coverage eventually. Chartered as [Charter joelclaw-api](./charter-joelclaw-api.svx); may spin into its own brief.
- **Video is a content resource (Joel, 2026-07-13):** rows live in the existing `contentResources` table with `type: "videoResource"`, course-builder style — typed schemas guard the `fields` bag at the code edge, never in storage.
- **joelclaw-api is the strangler (Joel, 2026-07-13, charter grill):** the new center of gravity, standalone repo, Bun+Hono on flagg tailnet-only, Effect HttpApi contract-first, XState v5 as the general workflow pattern, ultracite-with-ox-presets + tsgo. First bite: video + shortlinks; the 110+ Inngest fns, webhook gateway, and apps/web pages are no-touch until the pattern proves. It takes **full Convex custody** (convex/ moves out of apps/web; apps/web consumes types via `link:`) BEFORE phase 1 — strictly serial.
- **live-dashboard merges into the api stream (Joel, 2026-07-13):** apps/live-dashboard becomes a CLIENT of joelclaw-api — its convex functions migrate into joelclaw-api/convex and it never deploys Convex itself. Coordinated live with the live-dashboard session (wE:p1); contract recorded on [Separate Call Telemetry from the Sessions Table](./separate-call-telemetry-from-sessions.svx).
- **Runtime doctrine (Joel, 2026-07-14, post-phase-1 retro):** joelclaw-api runs on **Node** — the strangler gets the boring, maximally-compatible runtime (two of phase 1's four bugs were Bun-specific: aws-sdk stream hang, `write()` returns 0 for file bodies). system-bus stays Bun for now, but **node-ward migration is the vision**: the strangler is the migration vehicle — whatever it absorbs becomes Node+Effect, and Bun's surface shrinks bite by bite. No big-bang worker migration.
- **Effect goes deep via forensics (Joel, 2026-07-14):** the observability rewrite and Effect-ification are one job — `Effect.timeout` (tonight's hang dies in 30s not 10 minutes), `Config` (the :3210 default landmine), Schema-validated HTTP, `withSpan` → otel → ClickHouse. Ground idioms in `.agent_sources/github.com/Effect-TS/effect-smol`.
- **`.agent_sources` doctrine (Joel, 2026-07-13):** repos ground idiomatic Effect/XState in read-only upstream clones under `.agent_sources/github.com/<org>/<repo>` declared in AGENTS.md (see joelclaw-central, joelclaw-brain). joelclaw-api ships with effect, xstate, and hono archives from day one.

### Execution override

Phase 1 (file pointer → Mux → asset/playback id) and the Deepgram transcript flow are carried into the map as task tickets: they're the proof the rest of the map decides against, and later decisions (agent surface, watch page) need a real pipeline to measure. The Mux webhook repoint is also carried — it's plumbing the pipeline dies without.

### Yoink source

`badass-courses/course-builder` (checked out at `~/Code/badass-courses/course-builder`) — `packages/core/src/inngest/video-processing/` (events + functions: video-uploaded, video-ready, transcript-ready, add-srt-to-mux-asset, video-processing-error, remove-completed-video) and `packages/core/src/lib/mux.ts`. Yoink liberally; drop the Sanity/party-specific bits.

Prior art already in joelclaw: mux webhook provider (above), `packages/system-bus/src/inngest/functions/media-process.ts` (claim-check pattern, NAS at `joel@three-body`), `media-transcription-pipeline.ts`, `video-download.ts`.

